title: Cristiano Ronaldo sends sensitive lefties into ‘fits of unbridled rage’ following Trump praise
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi has commented on footballer Cristiano Ronaldo praising Donald Trump and revealing his desire to meet the US President.  “A trigger warning for the more sensitive lefties,” she said.  “That clip is going to send the left into fits of unbridled rage.”

title: ‘This lady has some issues’: Kimmel’s wife blasted for cutting ties with Trump-supporting family
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi reacts to Jimmy Kimmel’s wife Molly McNearney admitting to cutting ties with her Trump-supporting family.  Ms McNearney revealed she cut ties with family after sending them emails begging them not to vote for Donald Trump in last year’s presidential election.  She said she felt deeply betrayed by relatives who backed US President Donald Trump, saying their vote was effectively a vote against her TV host husband and family.  “I mean, I think this lady has some issues,” Ms Panahi said.

title: ‘The scandals never end’: Bombshell claims Andrew invited prostitutes to Buckingham Palace
description: Sky News contributor Sophie Elsworth reacts to reports disgraced former prince Andrew had prostitutes at Buckingham Palace, with claims that Queen Elizabeth was aware.  “It’s never a dull moment here with prince Andrew, or formally prince Andrew,” Ms Elsworth told Sky News host Chris Kenny.  “The scandals surrounding Andrew just never end, and the leaking around Andrew and his former wife Sarah Ferguson continues.  “The bad headlines just continue for him and, sadly, for the Royal Family; they cannot shake this.”

title: BBC under ‘immense pressure’ after two top bosses resign ‘in disgrace’
description: Sky News contributor Sophie Elsworth rips into the BBC for its “disgraceful conduct” after being accused of institutional bias.  This comes as the corporation is facing allegations a documentary misled viewers by editing a speech made by US President Donald Trump.  “The BBC is in crisis today, as we know the two top bosses resigned … in disgrace,” Ms Elsworth told Sky News host Chris Kenny.  “Now there is a massive spotlight on the BBC yet again because they’ve been accused of institutional bias for a series of reports.  “Every front page is about the BBC’s disgraceful conduct.”

title: Trump threatens to sue the BBC for $1 billion over 'false and defamatory' documentary clip
description: US President Donald Trump threatened to sue the BBC for $1US billion.  The threat relates to a BBC Panorama documentary about Trump's January 6, 2021, speech, which has faced widespread criticism.  During the documentary, there was a doctored recording of a speech he gave before the January 6 Capitol Hill riots, which quoted the president out of context.  In a letter sent to the BBC from Trump's legal team, they called on the company to retract the "false, defamatory, disparaging, and inflammatory statements" immediately.  The BBC Chair, Samir Shah, has since apologised for an "error of judgment" made within the documentary.  Following The Telegraph breaking the story, the BBC director general Tim Davie and the CEO of News Deborah Turness both resigned.

title: ‘Pathetic’: Prince Harry and Meghan Markle reduced to being ‘unapologetically tacky’
description: ‘Kinsey Schofield Unfiltered’ host Kinsey Schofield claims Prince Harry and Meghan Markle have been reduced to being “unapologetically tacky”.  “How pathetic and disappointing their priorities currently are,” she told Sky News host Rita Panahi.

title: Cops were called to Kris Jenner’s 70th birthday bash numerous times
description: ‘Kinsey Schofield Unfiltered’ host Kinsey Schofield has commented on the police being called to Kris Jenner’s 70th birthday bash numerous times.  Kris Jenner’s James Bond-themed 70th birthday bash, which was held at Jeff Bezos’ mansion, reportedly had the police called numerous times due to noise complaints from neighbours.  “Rules for thee but not for the elite,” Ms Schofield told Sky News host Rita Panahi.

title: Renewables rollout suffers setback as $1 billion super battery ‘beyond repair’
description: Grattan Institute Energy and Climate Change Director Tony Wood reacts to the catastrophic failure of NSW’s $1 billion super battery.  “This project was due to come online pretty soon, and it has three major transformers as part of the project … without those transformers, the battery can’t do its job,” Mr Wood told Sky News Australia.  “One of those transformers has failed; we don’t know yet what the nature of the failure was, but it was bad enough that it is considered to be beyond repair by the operators of that battery.”

title: ‘Ludicrous’: Blake Lively asks judge for $161 million in damages following Baldoni legal battle
description: ‘Kinsey Schofield Unfiltered’ host Kinsey Schofield has commented on actress Blake Lively asking a judge to award her $161 million in damages over Justin Baldoni’s alleged smear campaign against her.  Ms Lively claims she lost a whopping $56.2 million in earnings – past and future – from her acting and producing gigs, as well as speaking engagements and endorsements.  “I think she might receive something ... that number’s absolutely ludicrous,” Ms Schofield told Sky News host Rita Panahi.

title: Meghan Markle ‘embarrasses’ Prince Harry and sparks uproar with latest move
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi claims Meghan Markle has “embarrassed” Prince Harry after deciding not to wear a poppy alongside her husband at Kris Jenner’s 70th birthday party.  This is despite knowing of the Duke of Sussex’s deep and personal connection to Remembrance Day.  “Meghan’s upset plenty of people and possibly embarrassed Prince Harry,” Ms Panahi said.

title: Inbuilt left-wing bias warnings ‘ignored’ by the BBC
description: The Telegraph Associate Editor Gordon Rayner claims left-wing bias warnings were “ignored” by the BBC.   This comes as the corporation is facing allegations that a documentary misled viewers by editing a speech made by US President Donald Trump.  “I think for a long time, the BBC has had this sort of inbuilt liberal left-wing bias,” Mr Rayner told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “They clearly had an agenda.”

title: Mamdani’s ‘radical’ rhetoric and views on Israel lead to New York City’s ‘exodus’
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi discusses the “exodus” of people from New York City following Zohran Mamdani’s recent election win.  “The exodus from New York by those alarmed by Zohran Mamdani’s triumph there,” Ms Panahi said.  “The Mamdani refugees will be fleeing New York City, and among them will be sadly many Jews.  “Despite Mamdani’s radical rhetoric and anti-Israel views, the CNN exit polls show one in three Jews in New York City voted for him.”

title: BBC branded ‘ungovernable’ after top bosses quit amid Trump documentary scandal
description: The Telegraph Associate Editor Gordon Rayner questions whether the BBC is “governable” after two top bosses resigned.  This comes as the corporation is facing allegations a documentary misled viewers by editing a speech made by US President Donald Trump.  “I think the person who takes over from Tim Davie has got an absolutely enormous job on their hands,” Mr Rayner told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “There is a temptation to think that the BBC has become ungovernable because of the way that so many people that work there seem to come to work with an agenda.”

title: ‘Clear migration of businesses’: Millionaires ‘flee’ NYC following Mamdani’s election victory
description: Sky News host Freya Leach claims millionaires are “fleeing” New York following Zohran Mamdani’s election victory in the mayoral race.  “There is a clear migration of businesses and also personal wealth, and this is why high-taxing progressive policies actually hurt people overall,” she said.

title: BBC’s ‘egregious’ doctoring of Donald Trump’s speech was the 'nail in the coffin’
description: Sky News host Freya Leach claims the BBC’s edited footage of US President Donald Trump’s January 6 speech was the “nail in the coffin” for the national broadcaster.  “I think this was really the nail in the coffin because it was so obvious and so egregious,” she said.  Ms Leach claims the bias within the BBC is “systemic” and “broad-based”.
